	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Agricultural policy: CAADP compacts signed in Tanzania and Kenya</h1>

			
			<h4>
												06 September 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>In July 2010 the governments of Tanzania and Kenya signed a NEPAD Comprehensive Africa Agriculture Development Programme (CAADP) compact. At the signing ceremony, Tanzanian President Jakaya Kikwete reiterated the government’s commitments to agricultural development initiatives which will ‘lead to a meaningful transformation of the country’s agriculture’. He noted that in the past similar initiatives had been undertaken ‘without realising the desired outcomes of a modern and highly productive agriculture sector.’ In this context he described the signing of the CAADP compact as ‘a unique opportunity to complement his government’s efforts and enhance the contribution of the private sector to the development of the country’s agriculture.’</p><p>The roundtable meeting which coincided with the signing ceremony reached a consensus on a wide range of measures that were needed for the successful implementation of the Agricultural Sector Development Programme for Tanzania and the Agriculture Strategic Plan for Zanzibar. Mobilising external resources was seen as essential, with the signing of the CAADP compact opening up access to the special fund for CAADP signatories. The government of Tanzania is looking to exceed the target of allocating 10% of its national budget to agriculture: this is seen as essential in view of the ‘many challenges facing the sector’. The budget allocation to agriculture has already risen from 3% in 2005/06 to 9% in 2010/11.</p><p>In Kenya, the CAADP compact is seen as complementing the government’s new ‘Agriculture Sector Development Strategy 2012’, which aims to ‘achieve an agricultural growth of 7% per year over the next 5 years’ and establish agriculture as ‘a key driver for sustained economic growth’. At the signing ceremony, President Mwai Kibaki said that the government would ‘endeavour to create an environment that will enable the private sector to take over many of the commercial enterprises that are currently with the government.’ He committed the government to ‘policy, legal and regulatory reforms so that individual farmers feel encouraged to shift from subsistence production to market-oriented commercial production.’</p><p>Elsewhere in the East African Community, Uganda had signed its CAADP compact in March 2010, while Rwanda and Burundi had signed theirs in March 2007 and August 2009 respectively.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
