<a href="http://www.nepad-caadp.net/pdf/Burundi%20CAADP%20Compact.pdf" target="_self">http://www.nepad-caadp.net/pdf/Burundi%20CAADP%20Compact.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>CAADP is an Africa-led and African owned process which aims to help African countries reach a higher path of economic growth through agriculture-led development. It stems from a ministerial decision taken within the framework of the New Partnership for Africa’s Development (NEPAD). CAADP compacts seek to bind African governments to increasing public investment in agriculture to a minimum of 10% of their national budgets and to raise agricultural productivity by at least 6% per annum, with the ultimate aim of eliminating hunger and reducing poverty. Significantly CAADP now provides one of the main frameworks for the deployment of donor financing in support of agricultural development in Africa. Market access and agricultural trade issues form one of the four pillars of the CAADP programme.</p><p>Some 26% of EU assistance allocated to Kenya’s 10th EDF National Indicative Programme (NIP) for the period 2008-2013 (€98.8 million) is allocated in support of the Kenyan government’s ‘Strategy for the Revitalisation of Agriculture’, which sets out objectives in line with CAADP commitments. The EC was an active partner in the elaboration of the strategy, and looks well placed to support the implementation of the CAADP compact, given its existing programmes of support under the 10th EDF.</p><p>In Tanzania, under the 9th EDF, STABEX funding of some €44 million was used to support specific programmes (e.g. coffee sector research) and to contribute to sector budget support for the implementation of the Agriculture Sector Development Programme. Under Tanzania’s 10th EDF NIP, to which some €555 million was initially allocated, the main allocation is to general budget support (€305 million), with a focus on education and social services; a secondary allocation is to infrastructure, communication and transportation projects (€139 million); and some €55.5 million is allocated to trade and regional integration programmes, some of which focus on supporting the exploitation of market access opportunities under preferential trade arrangements, and therefore benefit the agricultural sector.</p><p>While pillar II of the CAADP (market access) is the main vehicle for trade-related programmes, it remains to be seen how the commitments made under the various regional and national CAADP compacts (such as the one signed by Kenya and Tanzania) will effectively improve the trade of agricultural products at the national, regional and international levels. As far as agricultural trade is concerned, implementation of the various CAADP compacts will also need to take into account the lessons learned from previous aid for trade (AfT) programmes to ensure a better articulation between trade and agricultural policies.</p>
		</div>
		
